Date: Sat, 6 Jun 2026 09:09:36 -0500
Subject: [PATCH 1/2] backend: derive structured-loop body/exit polarity from
 the CFG, not the stale break-kind hint (round-10 native-drops Blocker B)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

`lower_to_simple_ir` reconstructs a `while`/`for` loop as one linear
`loop_start … loop_break_if_false/_true … loop_continue … loop_end` op stream.
Which cond-block successor is the loop BODY (continue) versus the loop EXIT
(after_block) was chosen purely from the pre-TIR `loop_break_kinds` polarity
hint that `detect_loop_structure` records from the ORIGINAL `loop_break_if_*`
op. molt double-roundtrips through TIR — the per-function pipeline lifts
SimpleIR→TIR→SimpleIR, then the RC drop module phase relifts that SimpleIR→TIR,
runs drop insertion (critical-edge splits + edge-exact retain placement), and
lowers SimpleIR again. Across those lifts the SSA terminator builder's
`loop_break_if_false` then/else convention and the drop phase's back-edge
reshaping can flip which side of the cond block's `CondBranch` is the back-edge
body versus the loop exit, so the recorded hint goes STALE relative to the TIR
the final lowering actually sees.

Trusting the stale hint then SWAPS body_entry/exit_block: for a `while True:`
whose only exit is an inner `if …: break`, the post-drop cond block is
`CondBranch { then: <exit/Return>, else: <back-edge/continue> }`, but the
recorded `BreakIfFalse` makes the lowering take `then` as the body. The EXIT
(a Return block) becomes `body_entry` (so the body DFS finds only
Return-terminated blocks → all deferred → an empty structured body), and the
back-edge CONTINUE becomes `exit_block`. Native `loop_start` materializes an
`after_block`; the swapped `loop_break_if_false` marks it reachable and jumps to
it from the break-cleanup edge, but the matching `loop_end` (which is what
switches-to and fills the after_block) is dropped for that degenerate shape.
The after_block is left REACHABLE-BUT-EMPTY, and Cranelift's downstream
`unreachable_code` pass does `last_inst(block).unwrap()` for every
domtree-reachable block → an opaque `unreachable_code.rs:29`
`Option::unwrap() on None` panic deep in the backend, surfacing only when native
RC drops are active (`tests/differential/memory/rc_sites_loop_break.py`). The
historical "cranelift unreachable_code.rs:29 panic on double-break loops"
(catalogued June-3) is the same class.

Fix (root cause, in the lowering): derive body/exit polarity from the CFG —
reducibility is the ground truth. The loop BODY is the cond successor from which
the loop HEADER (`*bid`, the back-edge target) is reachable through in-loop
blocks; the EXIT is the successor that leaves the loop. A new
`successor_reaches_header` probe does a forward DFS from each cond successor,
excluding the loop-controlling cond block (so the body→cond→{body,exit} cycle
cannot make the exit side appear to reach the header). body_entry/exit_block AND
the emitted `loop_break_if_false`/`_true` polarity are then both chosen from that
CFG fact, consistent regardless of `break_kind` staleness. The recorded hint is
used only as a tie-break when the CFG is genuinely ambiguous (both/neither
successor reaches the header — an infinite loop or an exit that re-enters), which
preserves the pre-existing behavior for those shapes. Well-formed `while`/`for`
loops are unaffected (a reducible loop's body successor reaches the header and
its exit does not, so the derived polarity equals the old hint byte-for-byte;
verified `concat_while` still emits `loop_break_if_false`+`loop_continue`+
`loop_end`).

Defense-in-depth (in native codegen): add a fail-loud block-finalization
invariant at the single finalization authority in `function_compiler.rs`. After
the unreachable-orphan trap pass, assert that no entry-DFS-reachable block is
left empty (no terminator). A reachable empty block is a structured-codegen bug
(a predecessor branches into it but it was never filled) and is exactly what
Cranelift's `unreachable_code` pass dereferences; surfacing it here as an
actionable molt-level diagnostic that names the function and block converts any
future regression of this class into a clear error at the right layer instead of
an opaque Cranelift panic. This is a verification guard, not a workaround — the
orphan must be fixed in codegen/lowering, never papered over by trapping a
reachable block (that would change program semantics).

DORMANT-SAFE: native RC drop insertion stays gated OFF
(`target_uses_tir_drop_insertion` NativeCranelift => false, unchanged). The
lowering fix derives from the CFG, which for the dormant (non-drop-reshaped)
pipeline already agreed with the recorded hint, so production native output is
byte-identical; the finalization assertion holds for all dormant functions.
Both are pure correctness improvements that ALSO unblock the WASM/LLVM lanes,
which share `lower_to_simple_ir`, for the same swapped-polarity shape.

Verification (native RC drops temp-wired ON for the drop-path checks; everything
re-verified DORMANT for the committed state):
  * NEW e2e regression `tests/differential/basic/loop_while_true_break_drops.py`
    (single inner break, double break, value-carrying break, heap-condition
    break) — byte-identical to CPython, drops ON and dormant; zero panics.
  * `tests/differential/memory/rc_sites_loop_break.py` (the failing case):
    drops ON it now builds with zero panics, runs to 1000000, RSS plateaus at
    8 MiB; dormant byte-identical. The historical double-break shape is healed.
  * design-20 memory set: 14/14 byte-identical with native drops ON (was 13/14,
    `rc_sites_loop_break` the lone Blocker B); 16/16 byte-identical DORMANT
    (the 14 memory tests + the round-9 and round-10 regressions), MOLT_VERIFY_
    ANALYSIS=1 clean. The finalization assertion did NOT fire on any of them.
  * round-9 regression `loop_shared_preheader_latch_drops.py` stays byte-
    identical (drops ON and dormant).
  * Rust gates on the committed (dormant) state: `cargo test -p molt-backend
    --features native-backend --lib` 1023 passed/0 failed; `--features
    native-backend,llvm --lib` 1092 passed/0 failed; `cargo test -p molt-runtime
    --lib` 510 passed/16 ignored; `cargo clippy -D warnings` clean for both the
    native and native+llvm feature sets; final release-fast dormant build clean.

The native drop flip (`target_uses_tir_drop_insertion` NativeCranelift => true)
stays HELD: its activation protocol requires a clean full `tests/differential/
basic` sweep against the calibration oracle in a quiet window, which the current
multi-agent host contention (repeated harness SIGKILLs, exit 144) prevented from
running reliably. Blocker B itself is fixed and landed dormant-safe here; the
flip is batoned to round-11.

